prompt:
I'm building the snake mini-game for our badge hardware and the firmware rules are strict: after init, ZERO heap. No malloc/calloc/realloc anywhere in the module, no pointers inside the game struct, every byte of state lives in the struct itself so I can put it in static RAM. The body must be a ring buffer over fixed arrays (head index + length, wrap with modulo), not a linked list — that's the whole point of this ticket. Files: snake.h and snake.c, C17, stdint.h/stddef.h only, no I/O.

Header constants and surface:

    #define SNAKE_MAX_W    16
    #define SNAKE_MAX_H    16
    #define SNAKE_MAX_FOOD 32

    typedef struct snake snake;   /* define the struct in snake.h; self-contained, no pointers */

    int snake_init(snake *s, int w, int h, const uint8_t *food, int nfood);
    int snake_turn(snake *s, char dir);
    int snake_tick(snake *s);
    int snake_score(const snake *s);
    int snake_len(const snake *s);
    int snake_alive(const snake *s);
    int snake_render(const snake *s, char *buf, size_t cap);

Rules (the badge tests replay exact games, so follow these to the letter):

- Grid is w columns by h rows, x grows right, y grows down, cell (0,0) top-left. snake_init rejects (returns -1, touches nothing): NULL s, w or h outside [4,16], nfood outside [0,32], food NULL when nfood > 0, or any food coordinate off the grid. food is nfood (x,y) byte pairs — a fixture queue, consumed in order; our fixtures guarantee a food cell is never under the snake when it comes up, so place them as given. On success return 0: snake starts length 3 heading East, head at (w/2, h/2) with the two body cells directly to its left; the first queue entry (if any) is on the board.
- snake_turn(s, d): d is one of 'N','E','S','W'. Rejected with -1 (state untouched): anything else, a dead snake, or the exact reverse of the direction the snake last actually moved (its initial heading counts until the first tick). Accepted turns return 0 and take effect at the next tick; if several accepted turns land between ticks, the last one wins. Note the reversal check is always against the last MOVED direction, not against a pending turn.
- snake_tick advances one cell: returns -1 if already dead, 0 if this tick kills the snake (hitting a wall or its own body — the state stays frozen at the last legal position, alive drops to 0), 1 for a plain move, 2 for a move that eats. Eating = new head lands on the current food: length grows by one (the tail stays put that tick), score bumps, and the next queue entry appears (queue empty = no food on the board). Moving into the cell the tail is vacating this very tick is LEGAL when not eating — the classic tail-chase — but the tail does not vacate on an eating tick.
- snake_render draws the full frame into my buffer: a '#' border all the way round, '.' empty, '*' food, 'o' body, 'O' the head, each of the h+2 rows terminated by '\n', the whole thing NUL-terminated. That's (h+2)*(w+3) characters plus the NUL; if cap is smaller than that total, return -1 and leave the buffer alone, else return the character count (NUL excluded). Works on a dead snake too (last frozen frame).
- snake_score / snake_len / snake_alive: foods eaten, current body length, 1 or 0.

make test is the gate. Makefile, mintest.h, test_snake.c are fixed — don't touch them.
